WAYFARER PLATFORM
PRODUCT BIBLE
Feature ID: F-6.7.5 — Preference Memory (Persistent Structured Profile Memory)
Version 2.0  ·  April 2026  ·  Binding Doctrine
1. Why This Feature Exists
Every time a traveler uses the platform, they reveal something about how they like to travel. “I hate hostels.” “I prefer trains in Europe.” “Don’t give me early departures.” “I love astronomy.” Today, those signals live in voice transcripts and onboarding chips — but they’re not structured, not persistent, and not separated by scope.
Preference Memory captures those signals and organizes them into three layers: what the traveler means right now (session), what applies to this trip (trip), and what should be remembered forever (profile). It’s the system that makes the platform feel like it knows you.
The onboarding signal profile (SignalProfile in lib/onboarding/signal-profile.ts) is the seed. Preference Memory is the evolution. Every subsequent interaction can refine it.

Binds to: user_profiles.preferences (profile layer storage), voice_artifacts (raw input), trips.metadata (trip layer), F-6.5.8 incident preference_context (session layer, post-incident promotion), F-6.5.13 Deep Scan Itinerary Optimizer (inferred scan mode from accumulated preferences), F-6.7.4 Budget Intelligence (budget preferences are a subset of preference memory).
2. The Traveler’s Story
Story 1: The hostels conversation
Sarah is building a Europe trip. The platform suggests a hostel in Barcelona. She says: “I don’t like hostels.” The voice parse detects a preference signal. The platform asks: “Got it — no hostels for this trip, or should I remember that for all future trips?” Sarah says: “All trips.” The preference “no hostels” is stored in her profile-layer preferences. She never sees a hostel suggestion again.
Story 2: The incident preference promotion
During a flight cancellation incident, Marcus tells the platform: “I don’t want United. Get me on anyone else.” The F-6.5.8 Options Engine captures this as an incident-scoped preference: excluded_carriers = [‘United’]. After the incident resolves, the platform asks: “You said you don’t want United during this incident. Remember that for future trips?” Marcus says yes. The preference is promoted from incident scope to profile scope.
Story 3: The trip-specific override
Marcus normally prefers mid-range hotels (profile preference). For his anniversary trip, he says: “For this trip, budget hotels are fine — we’re spending on experiences instead.” The platform stores this in the trip layer. His profile preference remains “mid-range.” After the trip, the trip-layer override expires. His next trip defaults back to mid-range.
Story 4: The inferred preference
Over 5 trips, Sarah always rejects early-morning departure suggestions and picks afternoon flights. The platform notices the pattern and asks: “You’ve chosen afternoon flights on your last 5 trips. Should I remember that you prefer avoiding early departures?” Sarah confirms. The platform stores “avoid early departures” in her profile.
Story 5: Deep Scan mode inference
Marcus has accumulated preferences: loves astronomy, prefers off-the-beaten-path, enjoys hiking, avoids tourist traps. His profile looks like an Adventure & Off-Path traveler. When he initiates a Deep Scan, the platform pre-selects “Adventure & Off-Path” mode and says: “Running your scan in Adventure mode based on your travel style. Change?” He can accept or switch.
3. Three Memory Layers
3.1 Session Layer
What the traveler means right now. Stored transiently during a single interaction. Not persisted beyond the session unless explicitly promoted.
Storage: React state or sessionStorage. Not written to the database.
Example: “I want a direct flight this time.” — applies to the current search/suggestion, forgotten when the session ends.
Promotion path: system may ask “Remember this for future trips?” → if yes, moves to profile layer.
3.2 Trip Layer
What applies to this specific trip. Stored in trips.metadata.preference_overrides as a JSONB object.
Example: “For this Japan trip, I’m okay with budget hotels.” — overrides profile preference for this trip only. Does not carry to future trips.
Lifecycle: created during trip planning. Expires when trip is archived. Does not affect other trips.
3.3 Profile Layer
What should be remembered long-term. Stored in user_profiles.preferences.preference_memory as a structured array of preference objects.
Example: “I hate hostels.” “I prefer trains in Europe.” “I love astronomy.” — carries across all future trips.
Schema: each preference is an object: { id: uuid, category: string, statement: string, source: string, confirmed_at: timestamp, source_context: string }
Categories: accommodation, transport, food, activities, carriers, timing, destinations, general
Sources: voice_capture, behavior_inferred, incident_promotion, manual_entry
4. How Preferences Are Captured
4.1 Voice Capture
Any voice interaction containing a preference signal triggers extraction. The voice parse system (app/api/voice/parse/route.ts) already handles 7 context types. Preference signals can appear in any of them.
Detection patterns: “I don’t like X”, “I prefer X”, “I always want X”, “Never give me X”, “I hate X”, “I love X.”
When detected, the system asks which layer: “Should I remember this for all trips, just this trip, or just right now?”
Implementation note: voice-based preference extraction is a FUTURE enhancement. The first prompt builds the preference storage, review UI, and manual entry only. Voice integration requires updating the parse prompts for each context type.
4.2 Behavior Inference
The platform tracks repeated choices: always rejecting hostels, always picking afternoon flights, always choosing food experiences over nightlife. After a threshold (3–5 consistent choices), the system surfaces an inferred preference for confirmation.
“You’ve chosen afternoon flights on your last 5 trips. Should I remember that you prefer avoiding early departures?”
The traveler can: Confirm (→ profile layer), Dismiss (→ never ask again for this inference), or “Not always” (→ keep observing).
Implementation note: behavior inference is a FUTURE enhancement. The first prompt builds manual entry and review.
4.3 Incident Promotion
F-6.5.8 already captures incident-scoped preferences in incidents.preference_context JSONB (excluded_carriers, preferred_mode, routing_preference, budget_signal, etc.). After an incident resolves, Preference Memory offers to promote confirmed preferences to the profile layer.
The post-incident debrief screen should include: “During this incident, you said: {preference}. Want to remember this for future trips?” with Yes/No buttons.
Implementation note: this requires a modification to the incident resolution flow. Include in the first prompt as a post-resolution hook.
4.4 Manual Entry
The traveler can directly add, edit, and delete preferences from a dedicated preferences review page.
5. Confirmation Rules
CRITICAL: No preference is promoted to the profile layer without explicit user confirmation. The system may suggest, but it never silently writes.
• Voice: “Remember this?” → user says yes → stored
• Behavior: “We noticed you always do X. Remember?” → user confirms → stored
• Incident: “You said X during the incident. Keep?” → user confirms → stored
• Manual: user types it directly → immediately stored (they initiated it)
Exception: the onboarding signal profile (SignalProfile) writes are confirmed during the onboarding flow itself. Those are the seed data and follow existing onboarding confirmation patterns.
