6.3 Post-Incident Promotion Hook
After an incident resolution (when the traveler completes the claim routing flow), if the incident has a non-empty preference_context:
• Show a card: “During this incident, you mentioned these preferences:”
• List each preference with a checkbox: “Avoid United ✔” “Prefer direct flights ✔”
• Button: “Remember for future trips” → POST each checked preference to profile layer
• Button: “Skip — these were just for this incident” → dismiss
This appears on the incident resolution success screen, after the claim packet is generated.
7. Deep Scan Mode Inference
F-6.5.13 defines 6 scan modes: Cost Efficiency, Experience Density, Safety & Low-Friction, Adventure & Off-Path, Cultural Immersion, Rest & Recovery.
When the traveler initiates a Deep Scan, Preference Memory checks accumulated preferences for mode signals:
• “love astronomy” + “off-the-beaten-path” + “hiking” → suggests Adventure & Off-Path
• “budget hotels fine” + “cheap flights” → suggests Cost Efficiency
• “no extreme sports” + “prefer quiet hotels” + “avoid crowds” → suggests Rest & Recovery
The mapping is keyword-based against the preference statements, not LLM inference.
The scan pre-selects the inferred mode and shows: “Running your scan in {mode} based on your travel style. Change?” The traveler can accept or switch via dropdown.
Implementation note: mode inference is a FUTURE enhancement. The first prompt builds storage, review UI, manual entry, and post-incident promotion. Mode inference requires the Itinerary Optimizer to be built first (it’s currently specced in F-6.5.13 but not implemented).
8. Data Model
8.1 Profile Layer Schema (user_profiles.preferences.preference_memory)
Array of preference objects:
{ id: string (uuid), category: string, statement: string, source: 'voice_capture' | 'behavior_inferred' | 'incident_promotion' | 'manual_entry', source_context: string (e.g., 'incident_123' or 'onboarding_round_2'), confirmed_at: string (ISO timestamp), active: boolean (false = soft-deleted) }
8.2 Trip Layer Schema (trips.metadata.preference_overrides)
Partial object with any preference categories: { accommodation: string[], transport: string[], food: string[], activities: string[], carriers_excluded: string[], timing: string[] }
8.3 Security Classification
T2 (Sensitive). Preference data is personal. RLS: account-scoped via user_profiles existing policies. No preference data in logs, events, or error messages. Carrier preferences (excluded_carriers) are especially sensitive — do not expose in any analytics or aggregate views.
9. API Routes
Route	Method	Purpose
/api/account/preferences/memory	GET	Returns preference_memory array from user_profiles.preferences. Returns { preferences: PreferenceItem[] }.
/api/account/preferences/memory	POST	Add a new preference. Body: { category, statement, source }. Generates ID + confirmed_at. Emits preference_promoted_to_profile. Returns { preference }.
/api/account/preferences/memory/[id]	PATCH	Edit preference statement or category. Emits preference_updated (future event). Returns { preference }.
/api/account/preferences/memory/[id]	DELETE	Soft-delete: sets active = false. Emits preference_removed_by_user. Returns { success }.
10. FOCL Registration
Feature ID: F-6.7.5. Phase: 2. Default enabled: false. Soft dependencies: voice parse (future voice capture), F-6.5.8 (incident preferences for promotion), F-6.5.13 (Deep Scan mode inference — future).
When F-6.7.5 is inactive: Account page does not show “Travel preferences” row. Post-incident promotion hook does not appear. Deep Scan mode inference does not fire.
11. Governance Events
preference_promoted_to_profile — { preference_id, category, source, account_id }
preference_captured_from_voice — { preference_id, context_type, account_id } (future)
preference_inferred_from_behavior — { preference_id, pattern_description, confirmation_count, account_id } (future)
preference_confirmed_by_user — { preference_id, confirmation_type (voice/behavior/incident), account_id }
preference_removed_by_user — { preference_id, account_id }
12. Stress Behavior
Under PROTECTIVE: preference data remains readable and editable. Post-incident promotion continues to work (it’s user-initiated, not automated). No external API dependency. No degradation expected.
13. Test Obligations
E2E (tests/e2e/preference-memory.spec.ts):
• Navigate to /account/preferences/travel-memory → empty state renders correctly
• Add preference manually (“No hostels” in Accommodation) → appears in list with “You added this” badge
• Edit preference text → change persists on reload
• Delete preference → removed from list (soft-delete)
• Add 5 preferences across 3 categories → grouped display correct
Contract: preference data is account-scoped — user B cannot read user A’s preferences.
Post-incident promotion test (requires incident resolution flow): resolve incident with preference_context → promotion card appears → confirm → preference in profile layer.
